## 2. Open Interpreter — The Gold Standard for OS Control

### Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User Message"] --> B["OpenInterpreter.chat()"]
    B --> C["respond() generator"]
    C --> D["LLM generates code<br/>(Python/Shell/JS)"]
    D --> E{"User confirms?<br/>(unless auto_run=True)"}
    E -->|Yes| F["Computer.terminal.run(code)"]
    F --> G["Capture output"]
    G --> H["Feed output back to LLM"]
    H --> I{"Loop breaker detected?<br/>'The task is done.'"}
    I -->|No| C
    I -->|Yes| J["Return result"]
```

### Key Design Decisions

#### 1. The `Computer` API — 15 Submodules
Open Interpreter's `Computer` class is a clean abstraction of an entire computer:

```python
computer.mouse      # click, move, scroll, position
computer.keyboard   # type, press, hotkey
computer.display    # screenshot, width, height
computer.clipboard  # get, set
computer.browser    # search, open, scroll
computer.os         # info, platform, installed_apps
computer.terminal   # run shell commands
computer.vision     # OCR, find text in screenshot
computer.files      # list, read, write, search
computer.ai         # call LLM for subtasks
computer.skills     # saved reusable procedures
# ... plus mail, sms, calendar, contacts, docs
```

#### 2. Auto-Generated Tool Catalog
**This is what Autobot needs most from Open Interpreter.** They auto-extract tool signatures:

```python
def _get_all_computer_tools_signature_and_description(self):
    """Introspect all Computer submodules, extract method signatures + docstrings."""
    for tool in self._get_all_computer_tools_list():
        tool_info = self._extract_tool_info(tool)
        for method in tool_info["methods"]:
            formatted = f"{method['signature']} # {method['description']}"
            # Result: "computer.keyboard.hotkey(*keys) # Presses hotkey combination"
```

This generates a catalog like:
```
computer.mouse.click(x, y, button='left') # Clicks at coordinates
computer.keyboard.type(text, interval=0.05) # Types text character by character
computer.display.screenshot() # Takes screenshot, returns base64
computer.clipboard.get() # Returns clipboard contents
computer.browser.search(query) # Searches web and returns results
```

This catalog is **injected into the system message** so the LLM always knows exactly what tools are available and how to use them.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Autobot equivalent:** Your [_build_prompt()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py#319-385) passes `Allowed actions: ["browser_fill", "browser_click", ...]` — raw names with NO signatures, NO parameter docs. Adopting OI's auto-extraction pattern would immediately improve LLM accuracy.

#### 3. Code-First Execution
Open Interpreter doesn't pre-define actions. The LLM **writes code** that uses the `computer` API:

```python
# LLM generates:
computer.keyboard.hotkey('ctrl', 'c')
text = computer.clipboard.get()
computer.browser.search(f"translate {text} to French")
```

This is extremely flexible because the LLM can compose arbitrary operations. The tradeoff: it requires the LLM to write correct Python.

#### 4. Loop Control
Instead of a Planner/Executor/Verifier loop, OI uses a simpler pattern:
- A `loop_message` is automatically sent after each LLM response
- The LLM must respond with a `loop_breaker` phrase to terminate
- Example breakers: `"The task is done."`, `"The task is impossible."`, `"Please provide more information."`

---

## 3. Computer Use OOTB — Vision-Grounded GUI Agent

### Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User Task"] --> B["Planner LLM<br/>(GPT-4o / Qwen / Claude)"]
    B --> C["High-level plan:<br/>steps to achieve goal"]
    C --> D["Actor Model<br/>(ShowUI / UI-TARS)"]
    D --> E["Screenshot → Vision Model<br/>finds exact click coords"]
    E --> F["pyautogui.click(x, y)"]
    F --> G["Take new screenshot"]
    G --> H{"Goal achieved?"}
    H -->|No| D
    H -->|Yes| I["Done"]
```

### Key Design Decision: Planner/Actor Split

Computer Use OOTB separates two distinct concerns:

| Role | Model | What It Does |
|---|---|---|
| **Planner** | General LLM (GPT-4o, Qwen, Claude) | Understands the goal, breaks into steps, makes decisions |
| **Actor** | Vision-Language-Action model (ShowUI, UI-TARS) | Looks at screenshot, finds exact pixel coordinates to click |

The Planner says "Click the Submit button" and the Actor looks at the screenshot and says "Submit button is at (450, 320)." Then `pyautogui.click(450, 320)`.

This is fundamentally different from Browser Use's approach (use DOM indices) or Autobot's approach (guess CSS selectors). It relies on **visual understanding** of the screen, which works across any application (not just browsers).

> [!TIP]
> **Relevance to Autobot:** For OS-level control (opening apps, clicking desktop elements), this vision-grounded approach may be necessary. For browser tasks, Browser Use's DOM-based approach is more reliable and cheaper.

---

## 4. What Autobot Should Become — The Blueprint

Based on studying all 4 projects, here is the unified architecture that combines the best of each:

### Target Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User Goal"] --> B["Planner LLM<br/>(from Autobot autonomy.py)"]
    B --> C["Phase Decomposition<br/>(keep existing decompose_goal)"]
    C --> D["Executor Loop"]
    D --> E["Observe<br/>Browser: DOM tree + screenshot<br/>OS: screenshot + active windows"]
    E --> F["Build Context Message<br/>(Browser Use pattern:<br/>agent_state + browser_state + history)"]
    F --> G["LLM decides next actions<br/>(with full tool catalog<br/>+ structured output:<br/>thinking/eval/memory/goal/actions)"]
    G --> H["Execute actions<br/>(by DOM index for browser,<br/>by coordinates for OS)"]
    H --> I["Post-action observation<br/>(re-snapshot, detect page change)"]
    I --> J["Verifier<br/>(keep existing verify_progress<br/>+ add Judge pattern)"]
    J --> K{"Phase complete?"}
    K -->|No| D
    K -->|Yes| L{"More phases?"}
    L -->|Yes| C
    L -->|No| M["Done"]
```

### What to Take from Each Project

#### From Browser Use (Browser Intelligence)
1. **DOM-to-LLM pipeline:** Auto-snapshot every step, convert to indexed elements, send to LLM
2. **Click by index:** Eliminate CSS selector guessing. [click(index=4)](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/browser_agent.py#173-183) not [click(selector="button...")](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/browser_agent.py#173-183)
3. **Structured output schema:** `thinking` + `evaluation` + `memory` + `next_goal` + `action[]`
4. **System prompt template:** Detailed reasoning rules loaded from markdown file
5. **Page change detection:** After each action, check if URL/focus changed, skip remaining actions
6. **Loop/stall detection:** If no progress for N steps, force replanning
7. **Judge agent:** Separate LLM verifies task completion with screenshots

#### From Open Interpreter (OS Control + Tool Catalog)
1. **Computer API submodules:** `mouse`, `keyboard`, `display`, [clipboard](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/engine.py#1008-1016), [browser](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/engine.py#855-864), [os](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/browser_agent.py#129-137), `terminal`, `files`, `vision`
2. **Auto-generated tool catalog:** Introspect Python methods, extract signatures + docstrings, inject into prompt
3. **Code execution capability:** Let the LLM write arbitrary Python when needed (with safety guardrails)

#### From Computer Use OOTB (Vision Grounding)
1. **Screenshot-based action grounding:** For OS-level tasks, use vision model to find click coordinates
2. **Planner/Actor separation:** Use general LLM for planning, specialized model for low-level actions

#### From Autobot (Keep These)
1. **[autonomy.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/autonomy.py) loop:** Planner → Executor → Verifier cycle is solid
2. **Adapter concept:** Keep as high-level shortcuts for common multi-step operations
3. **Human profile mode:** Real Chrome profile with real cookies is a differentiator
4. **Dashboard/FastAPI:** Web interface for monitoring and control

### What to Delete from Autobot
1. **[workflows.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/workflows.py)** — 1000 lines of brittle hardcoded step sequences. The LLM should generate plans dynamically
2. **[planner.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/planner.py) keyword matching** — The `if lower.startswith("search ")` routing. Replace with LLM-driven planning
3. **CSS selector-based clicking** — Replace with DOM index-based clicking (Browser Use pattern)
4. **Flat action name lists in prompts** — Replace with rich tool catalog (Open Interpreter pattern)

---

## 5. Priority Decision: Where to Start

### Option A: "Browser Use Integration" (Recommended)
**Clone Browser Use's agent loop pattern into Autobot.** This means:
1. Replace the [decide_next_steps()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py#100-122) prompt with Browser Use's structured output schema
2. Auto-inject DOM tree (indexed elements) into every LLM call
3. Add page change detection after each action
4. Add the Judge verification pattern

**Estimated effort:** 2–3 weeks. **Impact:** Fixes the #1 problem (AI can't see the page).

### Option B: "Wrap Browser Use as a Library"
**Install `browser-use` as a dependency** and use it for all browser tasks. Focus Autobot on being the orchestrator + OS controller.

**Estimated effort:** 1 week for basic integration. **Risk:** Tight coupling to an external project.

### Option C: "Full Rebuild"
Fork Browser Use, fork Open Interpreter's Computer API, merge them into Autobot's autonomy loop.

**Estimated effort:** 4–6 weeks. **Risk:** Scope creep.

---

## 6. Concrete Mapping: Their Code → Your Code

| Their Component | Their File | Your Equivalent | What to Change |
|---|---|---|---|
| DOM extraction | `browser_use/dom/service.py` | [browser_agent.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/browser_agent.py) `browser_snapshot()` | Send snapshot output to LLM every step |
| Prompt building | `browser_use/agent/prompts.py` | [llm_brain.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py) [_build_prompt()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py#319-385) | Add `<browser_state>`, `<agent_history>`, structured output schema |
| System prompt | `system_prompts/system_prompt.md` | Inline strings in [llm_brain.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py) | Create [.md](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/README.md) template with reasoning rules, examples, action categories |
| Agent loop | `browser_use/agent/service.py` | [autonomy.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/autonomy.py) [_execute_phase()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/autonomy.py#191-284) | Add observe→think→act→verify cycle per step |
| Action execution | Pydantic `ActionModel` + `ActionRegistry` | [engine.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/engine.py) [_execute_action()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/engine.py#377-854) | Replace if/elif with registry pattern, use DOM indices |
| Tool catalog | `agent/views.py` + `ActionRegistry` | Not exists | Create `tool_catalog.py` with schemas for all actions |
| Computer API | `interpreter/core/computer/computer.py` | [engine.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/engine.py) (ad-hoc) | Create `computer/` submodules: mouse, keyboard, display, clipboard |
| Judge/Verifier | `agent/judge.py` | [llm_brain.py](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py) [verify_progress()](file:///c:/Users/User%201/OneDrive/Desktop/projects/django%20projects/personal%20projects/autobot/autobot/llm_brain.py#159-210) | Add screenshot to verification, use separate Judge prompt |

